she came back, she took Giles out sailing  

1738
02:28:48,479 --> 02:28:54,080
with her. I knew what had happened as soon as 
they came back. Beatrice and Giles never stayed  

1739
02:28:54,080 --> 02:28:59,600
at Manderley again. After that, I knew 
I could never trust Rebecca with anyone.

1740
02:29:00,640 --> 02:29:06,080
'She had a cousin, an awful man, called Jack 
Favell. He started to come here when I was away.'

1741
02:29:06,880 --> 02:29:12,399
'I've met him,' I said. 'He came here the 
day you went to London. I didn't tell you.  

1742
02:29:12,399 --> 02:29:14,000
I didn't want to remind you of Rebecca.'

1743
02:29:15,040 --> 02:29:19,280
'Remind me?' said Maxim. 'Oh God, 
I never needed to be reminded.

1744
02:29:20,240 --> 02:29:26,479
'Favell often stayed with Rebecca down at the 
cottage. He is a bad man. He's been in trouble  

1745
02:29:26,479 --> 02:29:31,679
with the police many times. I told Rebecca that I 
would shoot Favell if he came to Manderley again.

1746
02:29:33,120 --> 02:29:35,840
'Then, one night, I could 
stand our life here no longer.  

1747
02:29:36,720 --> 02:29:40,241
Rebecca came back from London very 
late. She went to the cottage.  

1748
02:29:40,960 --> 02:29:46,000
I thought Favell was with her. I went 
after them. I took a gun to frighten him.'

1749
02:29:47,359 --> 02:29:51,359
Maxim was talking in quick, short 
sentences. I held his hand tightly.

1750
02:29:52,560 --> 02:29:54,320
'I saw a light in the cottage and went in.  

1751
02:29:55,040 --> 02:29:58,479
To my surprise, Rebecca was 
alone. She looked ill and strange.

1752
02:29:59,520 --> 02:30:05,121
"This is the end," I told her. "I can't stand 
any more." Rebecca looked at me and smiled.

1753
02:30:05,920 --> 02:30:10,640
"It won't be easy to divorce me," she said. 
"Everyone believes our marriage is perfect."

1754
02:30:10,640 --> 02:30:12,480
'Then she stood up and walked towards me.

1755
02:30:13,359 --> 02:30:18,719
"If I had a child, Max," she said, "Everyone 
would think it was yours. You would like a son,  

1756
02:30:18,720 --> 02:30:24,000
wouldn't you? A boy to grow up at Manderley. 
And you would never know who his father was."

1757
02:30:25,120 --> 02:30:32,160
'And she smiled at me again. She was smiling when 
I killed her. The bullet went through her heart.'

1758
02:30:32,160 --> 02:30:35,200
Maxim's voice was very low. He spoke slowly.

1759
02:30:36,399 --> 02:30:41,280
'There was blood all over the floor. I had 
to get water from the sea to clean the place.

1760
02:30:42,240 --> 02:30:47,280
'There was no moon and it was very dark,' 
Maxim went on. 'I carried Rebecca's body  

1761
02:30:47,280 --> 02:30:53,120
to the boat. I laid the body on the floor of 
the cabin. Then I took the boat out into the  

1762
02:30:53,120 --> 02:30:58,000
bay. I wanted to take the boat a good way 
out, but the wind was too strong for me.

1763
02:30:59,280 --> 02:31:04,479
'I made some holes in the wooden planks with a 
metal spike. I opened the sea cocks and the sea  

1764
02:31:04,479 --> 02:31:11,359
water flowed in. In a few minutes it had covered 
my feet. I shut the cabin door behind me, climbed  

1765
02:31:11,359 --> 02:31:17,920
into the dinghy and rowed back. Rebecca's boat was 
already sinking. I sat and watched it go down.'

1766
02:31:19,359 --> 02:31:20,399
Maxim looked at me.

1767
02:31:21,680 --> 02:31:25,201
'That's all,' he said. 'There's no more to tell.'

1768
02:31:27,520 --> 02:31:32,560
The library was very quiet. We sat there together 
for some minutes without saying anything.  

1769
02:31:33,439 --> 02:31:35,120
Then Maxim began to speak again.

1770
02:31:36,800 --> 02:31:39,360
'I knew the boat would be found one day,' he said.  

1771
02:31:40,080 --> 02:31:44,399
'Rebecca knew she would win in the 
end. I saw her smile when she died.'

1772
02:31:45,760 --> 02:31:49,840
'But Rebecca is dead,' I told him. 
'That's what we must remember.'

1773
02:31:51,520 --> 02:31:55,840
'The diver has seen the body. They're 
going to get the boat up tomorrow morning.  

1774
02:31:56,720 --> 02:31:59,440
They'll find out that it's 
Rebecca's body in the cabin.'

1775
02:32:00,560 --> 02:32:04,480
'Then you must say you made a mistake about 
the other body. Nobody saw you that night.  

1776
02:32:05,120 --> 02:32:07,920
We are the only two people who know 
what happened that night, Maxim.'

1777
02:32:08,840 --> 02:32:12,080
'Yes,' he said. 'Yes, I suppose so.'

1778
02:32:13,040 --> 02:32:15,840
'They will think the boat sank when 
Rebecca went down into the cabin.  

1779
02:32:16,640 --> 02:32:21,040
They'll think she was trapped there. They'll 
think that, won't they, Maxim?' I said.

1780
02:32:22,640 --> 02:32:27,281
'I don't know,' Maxim replied 
slowly. 'I don't know.'

1781
02:32:29,200 --> 02:32:37,840
At that moment, the telephone in 
the next room began to ring.
 
 

1782
02:32:42,080 --> 02:32:43,040
CHAPTER NINETEEN

1783
02:32:43,760 --> 02:32:44,640
Colonel Julyan

1784
02:32:47,200 --> 02:32:52,080
Maxim went into the little room and closed 
the door. I sat there, listening to the sound  

1785
02:32:52,080 --> 02:32:58,000
of Maxim's voice. I was no longer afraid 
of Rebecca; I did not hate her any more.  

1786
02:32:59,040 --> 02:33:06,000
Maxim and I were going to fight this 
together. Rebecca had not won, she had lost.

1787
02:33:06,000 --> 02:33:11,520
'That was Colonel Julyan,' said Maxim, as he came 
back into the room. He is the local magistrate.  

1788
02:33:12,800 --> 02:33:15,840
He has to be there when they get 
the boat up tomorrow. He asked  

1789
02:33:15,840 --> 02:33:17,840
me if I had made a mistake about the other body.'

1790
02:33:19,120 --> 02:33:24,000
The telephone began to ring again. Maxim answered 
it quickly and came back into the library.

1791
02:33:25,200 --> 02:33:26,720
'It's begun,' he said.

1792
02:33:27,439 --> 02:33:29,040
'What do you mean?' asked.

1793
02:33:29,920 --> 02:33:34,800
'That was a reporter. The whole thing will be in 
the papers tomorrow. There's nothing we can do.'

1794
02:33:36,399 --> 02:33:39,200
After dinner, we went back 
into the library as usual.  

1795
02:33:40,160 --> 02:33:47,840
I sat at Maxim's feet, my head against his knees. 
In a strange way, we were completely happy.

1796
02:33:48,399 --> 02:33:52,799
Rain fell in the night. When I woke up in 
the morning, Maxim had already gone out.  

1797
02:33:53,600 --> 02:33:59,280
I went down to breakfast as usual. There were 
a lot of letters thanking us for the Ball. How  

1798
02:33:59,280 --> 02:34:06,559
far away that seemed! I felt calmer, much older 
now. I took the letters into the morning-room.  

1799
02:34:07,600 --> 02:34:12,800
To my surprise, the room was dusty and untidy. 
The windows were tightly closed and some of the  

1800
02:34:12,800 --> 02:34:18,480
flowers were dead. I rang the bell for a maid 
and when she came, I spoke to her angrily.  

1801
02:34:19,439 --> 02:34:22,080
I wondered why I had been 
frightened of the servants before.

1802
02:34:23,520 --> 02:34:27,840
The menu for the day lay on the desk. 
It was the same food as the day before.  

1803
02:34:28,560 --> 02:34:30,480
I crossed everything out and rang for Robert.

1804
02:34:31,680 --> 02:34:34,480
'Tell Mrs Danvers to order 
something different,' I told him.  

1805
02:34:35,680 --> 02:34:40,800
Then I went out into the garden and cut some 
roses. Very soon Maxim will be back, I thought.  

1806
02:34:41,439 --> 02:34:48,160
I must be calm and quiet. I took the roses back 
into the morning-room. It was clean and tidy now.

1807
02:34:49,439 --> 02:34:52,160
As I began to arrange the flowers, 
there was a knock at the door.

1808
02:34:53,120 --> 02:34:57,840
It was Mrs Danvers, holding the menu 
in her hand. She looked pale and tired.

1809
02:34:59,680 --> 02:35:04,720
'I don't understand,' she said. 'I'm not 
used to having messages sent by Robert.  

1810
02:35:05,359 --> 02:35:09,120
When Mrs de Winter wanted any change 
in the menu, she spoke to me herself.'

1811
02:35:10,160 --> 02:35:15,120
'I am Mrs de Winter now, Mrs Danvers,' I 
said. 'And I shall do things in my own way.'

1812
02:35:16,479 --> 02:35:17,839
Mrs Danvers stared at me.

1813
02:35:19,680 --> 02:35:22,000
'Is it true,' she asked slowly,  

1814
02:35:22,720 --> 02:35:27,360
'that Mrs de Winter's boat has been found 
and that there was a body in the cabin?'

1815
02:35:28,640 --> 02:35:31,120
'I am afraid I don't know 
anything about that,' I said.

1816
02:35:32,560 --> 02:35:38,241
'Don't you?' Mrs Danvers said. She 
stood looking at me. I turned away.

1817
02:35:39,760 --> 02:35:42,560
'I will give orders about the lunch,' she said.  

1818
02:35:43,920 --> 02:35:47,440
She waited, but I did not say 
anything. She went out of the room.

1819
02:35:48,640 --> 02:35:54,240
Mrs Danvers did not frighten me any more. 
She was my enemy and I did not care.  

1820
02:35:54,240 --> 02:35:58,559
But if she learnt the truth about Rebecca's 
death, she would become Maxim's enemy too.  

1821
02:35:59,600 --> 02:36:04,480
I suddenly felt sick and ill. I went out on 
to the terrace and began to walk up and down.

1822
02:36:05,760 --> 02:36:08,400
At half past eleven, Maxim 
phoned me from Frank's office.  

1823
02:36:09,040 --> 02:36:11,920
He told me he was bringing Colonel 
Julyan and Frank back for lunch.

1824
02:36:12,960 --> 02:36:17,520
The time dragged by. At five to one, I 
heard the sound of a car in the drive.  

1825
02:36:18,319 --> 02:36:22,080
Maxim came into the hall with 
Frank and Colonel Julyan.

1826
02:36:22,080 --> 02:36:26,559
Colonel Julyan, the magistrate, was a 
middle-aged man with a kind face and grey hair.

1827
02:36:27,760 --> 02:36:31,760
'This is most unpleasant for you and 
your husband,' Colonel Julyan said to me.  

1828
02:36:32,399 --> 02:36:34,000
'I feel very sorry for both of you.'

1829
02:36:34,000 --> 02:36:40,399
Maxim and Frank went on into the dining-room and 
Colonel Julyan continued to speak to me quietly.

1830
02:36:41,200 --> 02:36:46,000
'We found a body in the boat this morning. 
It is the body of the late Mrs de Winter.  

1831
02:36:46,800 --> 02:36:51,360
As you know, Mr de Winter identified the 
other body found in the sea as his wife.  

1832
02:36:52,160 --> 02:36:54,479
That makes things rather difficult for us now.'

1833
02:36:55,600 --> 02:36:58,320
The Colonel stopped suddenly as 
Maxim came back into the hall.

1834
02:36:59,359 --> 02:37:01,920
'Lunch is ready; shall we go in?' he said.

1835
02:37:03,200 --> 02:37:08,000
I did not look at Maxim during lunch. We talked 
about the weather and Colonel Julyan asked me  

1836
02:37:08,000 --> 02:37:13,359
about my life in France. Frith and Robert were in 
the room and no one wanted to talk about the boat.  

1837
02:37:14,319 --> 02:37:17,840
At last Frith served coffee 
and the servants left us.

1838
02:37:18,479 --> 02:37:22,240
'I wish an inquest wasn't 
necessary,' Colonel Julyan said,  

1839
02:37:22,800 --> 02:37:26,000
'but I'm afraid it is. I don't 
think it will take very long.  

1840
02:37:26,640 --> 02:37:30,960
De Winter will have to say that the body in 
the boat was the late Mrs de Winter. Then the  

1841
02:37:30,960 --> 02:37:35,760
boat-builder will say that the boat was in good 
order when he last saw it. This must be done.'

1842
02:37:37,280 --> 02:37:40,639
'That's quite all right,' 
Maxim said. 'We understand.'

1843
02:37:42,000 --> 02:37:47,439
'I suppose Mrs de Winter had to go down into 
the cabin for something. Then the door shut and,  

1844
02:37:47,439 --> 02:37:52,240
somehow, she was trapped there. Don't you 
think so, Crawley?' the Colonel asked Frank.

1845
02:37:53,040 --> 02:37:58,399
'Oh yes, of course,' said Frank. I had a 
sudden feeling that Frank knew the truth.

1846
02:37:59,600 --> 02:38:03,920
'The inquest will be on Tuesday 
afternoon,' Colonel Julyan told us.  

1847
02:38:03,920 --> 02:38:08,240
'We'll keep it as short as possible, but 
I'm afraid the reporters will be there.'

1848
02:38:09,439 --> 02:38:10,559
There was another silence.

1849
02:38:11,520 --> 02:38:13,840
'Shall we go into the garden?' I said.

1850
02:38:14,800 --> 02:38:18,640
We all stood on the terrace for a moment 
and then Colonel Julyan looked at his watch.

1851
02:38:19,520 --> 02:38:23,520
'Thank you for the lunch,' he said 
to me. 'I'm afraid I must leave now.  

1852
02:38:24,160 --> 02:38:25,519
Would you like a lift, Crawley?'

1853
02:38:26,640 --> 02:38:31,040
Maxim walked with them to the car. When they 
had gone, he came back to me on the terrace.

1854
02:38:32,080 --> 02:38:36,319
'It's going to be all right,' Maxim said. 
'There won't be any trouble at the inquest.  

1855
02:38:36,880 --> 02:38:40,640
There is nothing to show what I did. 
Colonel Julyan thinks she was trapped  

1856
02:38:40,640 --> 02:38:42,480
in the cabin and the jury will think that too.'

1857
02:38:43,600 --> 02:38:44,400
I said nothing.

1858
02:38:45,680 --> 02:38:50,880
'It's you I'm sorry for,' Maxim told me 
sadly. 'I don't care about anything else.  

1859
02:38:51,680 --> 02:38:57,840
I'm glad that I killed Rebecca. But I can't forget 
what this has done to you. You have lost that  

1860
02:38:57,840 --> 02:39:04,640
young, sweet look. And it will never come back. In 
twenty-four hours, you have grown so much older.'

1861
02:39:07,120 --> 02:39:09,840
Frith brought in the newspapers 
at breakfast the following day.  

1862
02:39:10,479 --> 02:39:15,200
The story was in all of them. There was a 
picture of Manderley and an awful one of Maxim.  

1863
02:39:16,080 --> 02:39:19,840
All the papers said that Rebecca's body 
had been found after the Fancy Dress Ball.  

1864
02:39:20,800 --> 02:39:26,240
They said how everyone had loved Rebecca. They all 
said that Maxim had married his young, second wife  

1865
02:39:26,240 --> 02:39:32,639
within a year of Rebecca's death. It all made a 
good story. Maxim's face went whiter and whiter.

1866
02:39:33,920 --> 02:39:36,319
I wondered what the papers would 
say if they knew the truth.  

1867
02:39:37,120 --> 02:39:40,880
That terrible word - murder - 
would be on every front page.

1868
02:39:42,240 --> 02:39:46,719
Frank was a great help to us. We had no more 
phone calls from reporters and no visitors.  

1869
02:39:47,520 --> 02:39:51,840
It was just a question of waiting 
- of waiting until Tuesday.

1870
02:39:52,640 --> 02:39:55,440
Maxim and I stayed quietly in 
the house or in the gardens.  

1871
02:39:56,240 --> 02:39:58,399
We did not walk in the 
woods or go down to the sea.  

1872
02:39:59,439 --> 02:40:05,839
The weather was very hot and the air was heavy. 
There were clouds, but the rain did not fall.
 
 

1873
02:40:16,319 --> 02:40:17,200
CHAPTER TWENTY

1874
02:40:17,840 --> 02:40:19,840
The Inquest

1875
02:40:21,279 --> 02:40:24,559
Tuesday came at last. The 
inquest was at two o'clock.  

1876
02:40:25,359 --> 02:40:27,839
After an early lunch, I drove 
into the town with Maxim.

1877
02:40:28,880 --> 02:40:34,080
'I think I shall stay here in the car,' I 
said. 'I won't come in with you after all.'

1878
02:40:34,080 --> 02:40:38,399
'I didn't want you to come,' Maxim said. 
'I wish you had stayed at Manderley.'

1879
02:40:40,160 --> 02:40:43,760
Maxim went off and left me sitting 
there. The minutes went by.  

1880
02:40:44,319 --> 02:40:49,120
I wondered what was happening at the inquest. I 
got out of the car and began walking up and down.

1881
02:40:50,080 --> 02:40:51,279
A policeman looked at me.

1882
02:40:52,880 --> 02:40:58,319
'Excuse me, Madam,' he said. 'Aren't you Mrs 
de Winter? You can wait inside if you like.'

1883
02:40:59,600 --> 02:41:03,680
The policeman took me into an empty room. 
Five minutes passed. Nothing happened.  

1884
02:41:04,240 --> 02:41:08,160
I got up and walked out of the little room. 
The policeman was still standing there.

1885
02:41:09,200 --> 02:41:11,200
'How long will they be?' I asked him.

1886
02:41:12,000 --> 02:41:16,240
'I'll go and see if you like,' the policeman 
said. He was back again in a moment.

1887
02:41:17,359 --> 02:41:23,200
'It won't last much longer,' he told me. 'Mr de 
Winter has just finished giving his evidence.  

1888
02:41:23,200 --> 02:41:25,760
There's only the boat-builder, 
Mr Tabb, to speak now.  

1889
02:41:26,479 --> 02:41:29,839
Would you like to go in? There's 
an empty seat near the door.'

1890
02:41:30,960 --> 02:41:36,800
I followed the policeman. He opened the door 
for me and I went in quietly and sat down. The  

1891
02:41:36,800 --> 02:41:44,560
room was small and full of people. The air was hot 
and stuffy. Frank was sitting next to Maxim. To my  

1892
02:41:44,560 --> 02:41:50,960
surprise, Mrs Danvers was there too, with Favell 
beside her. I wondered whether Maxim had seen him.

1893
02:41:52,399 --> 02:41:58,240
Tabb, the boat-builder, standing in the centre of 
the room, was answering the Coroner's questions.

1894
02:41:58,240 --> 02:42:01,439
'Was the boat in good condition?' 
the Coroner was asking.

1895
02:42:02,560 --> 02:42:05,680
'Yes, it certainly was the last time I saw it,'  

1896
02:42:06,240 --> 02:42:11,840
Tabb said. 'It was a strong little boat. I 
can't understand why it sank that night.'

1897
02:42:13,279 --> 02:42:15,679
'Accidents have happened 
before,' the Coroner said.  

1898
02:42:16,560 --> 02:42:19,520
'Mrs de Winter was careless 
for a moment and she died.'

1899
02:42:20,720 --> 02:42:25,840
'Excuse me, sir,' said the boat-builder. 
'I would like to say something else.'

1900
02:42:27,120 --> 02:42:29,840
'Very well, go on,' said the Coroner.

1901
02:42:30,640 --> 02:42:36,319
'It's this, sir. There was nothing wrong 
with that boat when I last saw it. So  

1902
02:42:36,319 --> 02:42:43,279
what I want to know is this. Who made those 
holes in the planks? Rocks didn't do it.  

1903
02:42:44,000 --> 02:42:48,960
The boat sank too far away from them. And 
those holes were mad with something sharp.'

1904
02:42:50,240 --> 02:42:53,840
I could not look at anyone. 
I stared down at the floor.

1905
02:42:54,720 --> 02:42:57,040
For a moment, the Coroner 
was too surprised to speak.  

1906
02:42:57,760 --> 02:43:01,600
Then he said, 'What do you 
mean? What sort of holes?'

1907
02:43:02,960 --> 02:43:05,840
'There were three of them, in 
different parts of the boat.  

1908
02:43:06,560 --> 02:43:10,720
And that's not all. The sea-cocks 
had been turned full on.'

1909
02:43:11,920 --> 02:43:15,649
'The sea-cocks? What are they?' asked the Coroner.

1910
02:43:15,649 --> 02:43:19,680
'The sea-cocks close the pipes 
leading to the wash-basins, sir.  

1911
02:43:20,240 --> 02:43:25,920
They must be kept tightly closed when the boat 
is sailing. Otherwise the sea water comes in.'

1912
02:43:27,200 --> 02:43:31,760
It was hot in that crowded room, far too 
hot. I wished someone would open a window.  

1913
02:43:32,399 --> 02:43:33,920
The boat-builder was speaking again.

1914
02:43:34,960 --> 02:43:40,880
'With those holes, sir, and the sea-cocks open, 
a small boat like Mrs de Winter's would soon  

1915
02:43:40,880 --> 02:43:46,960
sink. It's my opinion that there was no 
accident. That boat was sunk on purpose.'

1916
02:43:48,240 --> 02:43:53,279
I must try and get out of the door, 
I thought. There was no air. People  

1917
02:43:53,279 --> 02:43:58,160
were standing up and talking loudly. I 
heard the Coroner say, 'Mr de Winter.'

1918
02:43:59,279 --> 02:44:01,759
Maxim was standing up. I could not look at him.

1919
02:44:02,720 --> 02:44:04,800
'Mr de Winter,' the Coroner said,  

1920
02:44:05,439 --> 02:44:09,599
'you have heard James Tabb's evidence. 
Do you know anything about those holes?'

1921
02:44:10,880 --> 02:44:11,380
'Nothing.'

1922
02:44:12,560 --> 02:44:14,081
'Can you think why they are there?'

1923
02:44:15,359 --> 02:44:16,559
'No, of course not.'

1924
02:44:17,840 --> 02:44:20,319
'This news is a shock to you, of course?'

1925
02:44:21,600 --> 02:44:25,201
'Of course it is a shock. Does it 
surprise you that I am shocked?'

1926
02:44:26,080 --> 02:44:27,840
Maxim's voice was hard and angry.

1927
02:44:28,800 --> 02:44:31,840
Oh God, I thought, don't 
let Maxim lose his temper.

1928
02:44:32,800 --> 02:44:34,240
The Coroner was speaking again.

1929
02:44:35,359 --> 02:44:39,599
'Mr de Winter, I want to find out 
exactly how your late wife died.  

1930
02:44:40,160 --> 02:44:42,160
Who looked after Mrs de Winter's boat?'

1931
02:44:43,279 --> 02:44:44,559
'She looked after it herself.'

1932
02:44:45,840 --> 02:44:52,000
'Then whoever took the boat out that night also 
made those holes and opened the sea-cocks.'

1933
02:44:53,040 --> 02:44:53,920
'I suppose so.'

1934
02:44:55,359 --> 02:44:58,799
'You have told us that the door and 
windows of the cabin were shut?'

1935
02:44:59,760 --> 02:45:00,260
'Yes.'

1936
02:45:01,120 --> 02:45:03,920
'Doesn't this seem very 
strange to you, Mr de Winter?'

1937
02:45:04,720 --> 02:45:05,760
'Yes, it does.'

1938
02:45:07,200 --> 02:45:10,240
'Mr de Winter, I'm afraid I 
must ask you one other question.  

1939
02:45:10,880 --> 02:45:14,720
Were you and the late Mrs 
de Winter happily married?'

1940
02:45:16,080 --> 02:45:20,479
It was hot, so hot. I tried 
to stand up, but I could not.  

1941
02:45:21,279 --> 02:45:25,759
The ground came up to meet me. And then 
I heard Maxim's voice, clear and strong.

1942
02:45:26,640 --> 02:45:29,440
'Will someone take my wife 
outside? She is going to faint.'

1943
02:45:32,080 --> 02:45:35,120
I was sitting in the little 
room again. Frank was beside me.

1944
02:45:36,160 --> 02:45:39,680
'I'm sorry,' I said. 'It was so hot in there.'

1945
02:45:40,880 --> 02:45:43,760
'Are you feeling better, 
Mrs de Winter?' Frank asked.  

1946
02:45:44,399 --> 02:45:48,799
'Maxim has told me to take you back to 
Manderley.' Frank helped me to get up.

1947
02:45:49,680 --> 02:45:53,440
'I'd much rather stay,' I said. 
'I want to wait for Maxim.'

1948
02:45:54,640 --> 02:45:59,920
'Maxim may be some time,' Frank told me. 
'They may have to go over the evidence again.'

1949
02:46:00,720 --> 02:46:02,320
'But what are they trying to find out?'

1950
02:46:03,359 --> 02:46:07,679
Frank did not answer. We were in his 
car now and he was driving very fast.

1951
02:46:09,120 --> 02:46:13,279
'Did you see Favell there?' I asked. 
'He was sitting with Mrs Danvers.  

1952
02:46:14,319 --> 02:46:16,719
I don't trust them, Frank. 
They might make trouble.'

1953
02:46:18,000 --> 02:46:23,840
Frank did not answer. He could not know how much 
Maxim had told me. Then we were back at Manderley.

1954
02:46:24,800 --> 02:46:30,000
'Will you be all right now?' Frank asked 
me. 'I shall go back. Maxim may want me.'  

1955
02:46:31,040 --> 02:46:33,439
He got quickly back into the 
car again and drove away.

1956
02:46:34,800 --> 02:46:40,399
I went upstairs to my room, and lay down on 
my bed. What were they all saying now? What  

1957
02:46:40,399 --> 02:46:44,799
was happening? What would I do if Frank 
came back to Manderley without Maxim?  

1958
02:46:45,920 --> 02:46:48,560
I thought again of that dreadful word - murder.  

1959
02:46:49,520 --> 02:46:53,760
God, let me not think about it. Let me 
think about something else, anything...

1960
02:46:56,720 --> 02:47:03,760
I must have fallen asleep. I woke up suddenly. It 
was five o'clock. I got up and went to the window.  

1961
02:47:04,479 --> 02:47:08,240
There was no wind. Lightning 
flashed against the grey sky.  

1962
02:47:09,040 --> 02:47:13,200
I heard thunder in the distance. 
A few drops of rain began to fall.

1963
02:47:14,479 --> 02:47:19,839
I went downstairs and sat 
with Jasper in the library.
 
 

1964
02:47:26,800 --> 02:47:28,560
CHAPTER TWENTY ONE

1965
02:47:28,560 --> 02:47:30,000
A Visit From Jack Favell

1966
02:47:31,920 --> 02:47:34,800
It was after six when I heard 
the sound of Maxim's car.  

1967
02:47:35,680 --> 02:47:39,520
I tried to stand up but my legs were so 
weak that I had to lean against a chair.  

1968
02:47:40,640 --> 02:47:45,120
Maxim came into the room and stood 
by the door. He looked tired and old.

1969
02:47:46,399 --> 02:47:52,559
'It's all over,' he said. I waited. I 
could not speak or walk towards him.

1970
02:47:53,680 --> 02:47:59,360
'Suicide,' Maxim said. 'That's the verdict. 
They said that Rebecca killed herself.'

1971
02:48:00,640 --> 02:48:06,880
I sat down. 'Suicide,' I repeated. 
'Why do they think Rebecca did that?'

1972
02:48:08,240 --> 02:48:10,000
'God knows,' Maxim said.  

1973
02:48:11,279 --> 02:48:17,439
He went and stood by the window. 'There's one more 
thing to be done. Rebecca's body has to be buried.  

1974
02:48:18,560 --> 02:48:22,161
I'm going down to the church now. We'll 
talk about everything when I get back.  

1975
02:48:23,359 --> 02:48:29,759
We've got to start our lives all over again. The 
past can't hurt us if we are together. We'll have  

1976
02:48:29,760 --> 02:48:35,840
children too, I promise you. I must go now. I'm 
meeting Frank and Colonel Julyan at the church.'  

1977
02:48:37,439 --> 02:48:40,879
He left the room quickly and then I 
heard the sound of his car driving away.

1978
02:48:42,720 --> 02:48:47,760
It was quiet in the library. I thought about the 
church where Rebecca was being buried at last.

1979
02:48:49,520 --> 02:48:54,160
Just before seven, the rain began to fall 
heavily. I opened the windows to let in the  

1980
02:48:54,160 --> 02:48:59,279
cold, clean air. The rain was falling so 
heavily that I did not hear Frith come in.

1981
02:49:00,720 --> 02:49:07,280
'Excuse me, Madam,' he said. 'There's a 
gentleman to see Mr de Winter. It's Mr Favell.'

1982
02:49:08,560 --> 02:49:09,600
I was very surprised.

1983
02:49:11,040 --> 02:49:15,439
'I think I had better see Mr Favell,' 
I said. 'Bring him in here, please,  

1984
02:49:15,439 --> 02:49:22,559
Frith.' I hoped that Favell would go before Maxim 
came back. I could not think why Favell had come.

1985
02:49:24,160 --> 02:49:28,000
'I'm afraid Maxim is not here,' I 
said, when Favell walked into the room.  

1986
02:49:29,120 --> 02:49:32,240
His eyes were red. I wondered 
if he had been drinking.

1987
02:49:33,439 --> 02:49:38,559
'I don't mind waiting,' Favell replied. 
'Max will be back for dinner, I'm sure.'

1988
02:49:39,600 --> 02:49:44,320
'Mr Favell,' I said. 'I don't want 
to be rude, but I am very tired.  

1989
02:49:45,200 --> 02:49:47,040
It will be better if you 
come back in the morning.'

1990
02:49:47,840 --> 02:49:52,160
'No, no,' he said, coming towards me, 
'I've got something to say to Max.  

1991
02:49:52,960 --> 02:49:56,480
This has been a shock to me, you 
know. I was very fond of Rebecca.'

1992
02:49:57,439 --> 02:50:00,319
'Yes, of course,' I said. 
'I'm very sorry for you.'

1993
02:50:01,359 --> 02:50:04,639
'I was fonder of Rebecca than 
of anyone else in the world,'  

1994
02:50:04,640 --> 02:50:10,000
Favell went on. 'And she was fond of me. That's 
why I've come here to find out the truth.  

1995
02:50:10,880 --> 02:50:16,240
Suicide... my God. You and I know 
it wasn't suicide, don't we?'

1996
02:50:17,439 --> 02:50:22,240
As Favell was speaking, the door 
opened and Maxim and Frank came in.

1997
02:50:22,240 --> 02:50:25,120
'What the hell are you doing 
here?' Maxim said to Favell.

1998
02:50:26,080 --> 02:50:32,240
'Why, hello, Max, old man,' Favell said. 'You 
must be feeling very pleased with yourself.'

1999
02:50:33,680 --> 02:50:38,320
'Do you mind leaving the house?' said 
Maxim coldly. 'I don't want you here.'

2000
02:50:39,520 --> 02:50:46,000
'Now, wait a minute, Max,' Favell answered. 
'You've been very lucky. But I can still  

2001
02:50:46,000 --> 02:50:52,000
make life unpleasant for you. And dangerous 
too, perhaps.' Maxim stared hard at Favell.

2002
02:50:53,040 --> 02:50:57,040
'Oh yes?' he said. 'In what way 
can you make things dangerous?'

2003
02:50:58,800 --> 02:51:02,640
'I'll tell you, Max,' said 
Favell with an unpleasant smile.  

2004
02:51:03,439 --> 02:51:07,200
'You know all about Rebecca and 
me. Her death was a great shock.  

2005
02:51:07,920 --> 02:51:12,240
Then I read about Rebecca's boat and 
the body in the cabin. So I went to the  

2006
02:51:12,240 --> 02:51:17,840
inquest. I heard the boat-builder's evidence. 
What about those holes in the boat, Max?'

2007
02:51:19,120 --> 02:51:24,720
'You heard the verdict,' Maxim told him. 'I 
have nothing more to say.' Favell laughed.

2008
02:51:25,600 --> 02:51:30,880
'You know Rebecca didn't kill herself. I've 
a note here that may interest you. I kept  

2009
02:51:30,880 --> 02:51:34,080
it because it was the last thing 
Rebecca ever wrote to me. Listen.'

2010
02:51:35,520 --> 02:51:40,400
Favell took a piece of paper from his pocket. 
I recognized Rebecca's hard, black writing.

2011
02:51:42,000 --> 02:51:44,960
"I tried to phone you," Favell 
read, "but you were out.  

2012
02:51:45,520 --> 02:51:49,680
I'm leaving London now and going back 
to Manderley. I'll wait for you in  

2013
02:51:49,680 --> 02:51:55,760
the cottage. Come down as soon as you 
can. I've got something to tell you." '

2014
02:51:55,760 --> 02:51:57,600
Favell put the note back in his pocket.

2015
02:51:58,640 --> 02:52:03,201
'I found that in my London flat. It was 
too late to drive down to Manderley.  

2016
02:52:03,840 --> 02:52:06,160
When I phoned the following day, Rebecca was dead.  

2017
02:52:06,880 --> 02:52:09,840
Do you really think Rebecca killed 
herself after writing that note?'

2018
02:52:11,200 --> 02:52:12,240
Maxim said nothing.

2019
02:52:13,680 --> 02:52:21,279
'Now, Max, old man,' Favell said at last, 
'you know I'm not a rich man. If I had two  

2020
02:52:21,279 --> 02:52:28,080
or three thousand pounds, I could live quite 
well. I'd never come back, I promise you.'

2021
02:52:28,080 --> 02:52:32,960
'I've already asked you to leave the house,' 
Maxim said. 'The door is behind you.'

2022
02:52:33,920 --> 02:52:35,040
Favell laughed again.

2023
02:52:36,160 --> 02:52:38,399
'Think again, Max,' said Favell.  

2024
02:52:39,200 --> 02:52:43,200
'I don't suppose your new bride wants 
to be known as the wife of a murderer.'

2025
02:52:44,399 --> 02:52:47,120
'You can't frighten me, Favell,' Maxim answered.  

2026
02:52:47,840 --> 02:52:51,279
'Shall I phone Colonel Julyan? 
You can tell your story to him.'

2027
02:52:52,080 --> 02:52:58,080
'You wouldn't dare, Max,' said Favell. 'I 
have enough evidence to hang you, Max.'

2028
02:52:59,279 --> 02:53:02,000
Maxim walked slowly towards 
the telephone in the next room.

2029
02:53:02,560 --> 02:53:05,440
'Stop him,' I said to Frank. 
'Stop him for God's sake.'  

2030
02:53:06,000 --> 02:53:08,640
But it was too late. Maxim was already speaking.

2031
02:53:09,680 --> 02:53:14,320
'Is that Colonel Julyan? It's de Winter here. 
Could you come over to Manderley at once?  

2032
02:53:15,120 --> 02:53:19,519
No - I can't say anything over the 
phone. Thank you very much, goodbye.'

2033
02:53:21,359 --> 02:53:24,240
Maxim came back again into the room.

2034
02:53:24,240 --> 02:53:26,719
'Colonel Julyan will be here 
in ten minutes,' he said.

2035
02:53:27,840 --> 02:53:32,319
We waited in silence. The rain was so heavy 
that we did not hear the sound of the car.  

2036
02:53:33,120 --> 02:53:36,720
We were taken by surprise when Frith 
brought the magistrate into the library.

2037
02:53:37,760 --> 02:53:40,560
'Good evening, Colonel 
Julyan,' Maxim said at once.  

2038
02:53:41,120 --> 02:53:45,359
'This is Jack Favell, my late wife's 
cousin. He has something to say to you.'

2039
02:53:46,319 --> 02:53:51,040
Favell went up to Colonel Julyan. 
'I'm not happy about the verdict.  

2040
02:53:51,040 --> 02:53:56,399
I want you to read this note. Tell me whether you 
think the writer had decided to kill herself.'  

2041
02:53:57,680 --> 02:53:59,920
Colonel Julyan took the note and read it slowly.

2042
02:54:01,520 --> 02:54:05,840
'I see what you mean,' he said. 
'But the note is not clear.  

2043
02:54:06,479 --> 02:54:11,200
What do you think really happened to 
Mrs de Winter?' Favell looked at Maxim.

2044
02:54:12,720 --> 02:54:18,800
'I'll tell you what I think,' he said slowly. 
'Rebecca never opened those sea-cocks.  

2045
02:54:19,439 --> 02:54:23,359
She didn't make those holes in the 
boat. Rebecca didn't kill herself.  

2046
02:54:23,359 --> 02:54:28,880
I say she was murdered. Do you want to 
know who the murderer is? He's there,  

2047
02:54:28,880 --> 02:54:36,480
standing by the window. Mr Maximilian de Winter 
- he's your murderer. Take a good look at him.'

2048
02:54:38,080 --> 02:54:47,840
Favell began to laugh, a high stupid laugh, as he 
twisted the note round and round in his fingers.
 
 

2049
02:55:00,000 --> 02:55:01,760
CHAPTER TWENTY TWO

2050
02:55:01,760 --> 02:55:02,880
Rebecca's Diary

2051
02:55:05,920 --> 02:55:11,359
Thank God for Favell's laugh. I saw a look 
of disgust come into Colonel Julyan's face.

2052
02:55:12,479 --> 02:55:15,839
'The man's drunk,' he said quickly. 
'He doesn't know what he's saying.'

2053
02:55:16,560 --> 02:55:19,760
'Drunk, am I?' shouted Favell. 'Oh no,  

2054
02:55:19,760 --> 02:55:24,240
I'm not drunk. Max de Winter murdered 
Rebecca, and I'm going to prove it.'

2055
02:55:25,040 --> 02:55:29,840
'Wait a minute,' said Colonel 
Julyan. 'I want to hear your proof.'

2056
02:55:30,560 --> 02:55:35,600
'Proof?' said Favell. 'Aren't those 
holes in the boat enough proof for you?'

2057
02:55:36,560 --> 02:55:41,600
'Certainly not,' said Colonel Julyan. 'Unless 
you can find someone who saw him do it.'

2058
02:55:43,040 --> 02:55:49,279
'I'll get your proof for you,' shouted Favell. 
'De Winter killed Rebecca because of me.  

2059
02:55:50,000 --> 02:55:55,359
He was jealous because she loved me. He went 
down to the cottage and killed her there.  

2060
02:55:55,920 --> 02:55:59,520
Wait a minute... I think I 
can find someone who saw him.'

2061
02:56:00,880 --> 02:56:03,760
I suddenly knew what Favell meant. Someone had  

2062
02:56:03,760 --> 02:56:08,400
seen it all happen - someone who was 
often down there in the bay - Ben.

2063
02:56:09,840 --> 02:56:13,520
'There's an idiot who was always 
around the cottage,' Favell said.  

2064
02:56:13,520 --> 02:56:16,800
'He often slept on the beach. 
I'm sure he saw everything.'

2065
02:56:18,240 --> 02:56:21,200
'Can we get this man and question 
him?' asked Colonel Julyan.

2066
02:56:22,560 --> 02:56:27,600
'Of course,' said Maxim. 'His name 
is Ben. Could you go and get him,  

2067
02:56:27,600 --> 02:56:34,800
Frank? Take your car.' Frank went out quickly. 
Favell laughed angrily. His face was very red.  

2068
02:56:35,920 --> 02:56:40,319
'You all help each other down here, don't 
you?' he said. 'Crawley knows the truth,  

2069
02:56:40,319 --> 02:56:45,040
I'm sure. He'll be there to hold the young 
bride's arm when Max is sentenced to death.'

2070
02:56:46,319 --> 02:56:49,439
Without warning, Maxim went 
up to Favell and hit him hard.  

2071
02:56:50,080 --> 02:56:54,399
Favell fell heavily to the floor. I 
wished that Maxim had not hit him.  

2072
02:56:55,040 --> 02:56:59,680
Favell got slowly to his feet, walked over to 
a small table and poured himself some whisky.  

2073
02:57:00,560 --> 02:57:05,840
I saw Colonel Julyan look thoughtfully at Maxim. 
Was he beginning to believe Favell's story?

2074
02:57:06,880 --> 02:57:08,560
The door opened and Frank came in.

2075
02:57:10,080 --> 02:57:13,359
'All right, Ben,' he said 
quietly. 'Don't be frightened.'

2076
02:57:14,800 --> 02:57:19,600
Ben stepped into the room and stared at everyone 
with his small eyes. Favell walked up to him.

2077
02:57:20,560 --> 02:57:24,800
'You know who I am, don't you?' 
he said. Ben did not answer.

2078
02:57:25,520 --> 02:57:29,520
'Come on,' said Favell. 'You've seen 
me in the cottage, haven't you?'

2079
02:57:30,800 --> 02:57:37,680
Ben held Frank's arm. 'I've never seen him,' 
he said. 'Is he going to take me away?'

2080
02:57:38,960 --> 02:57:45,680
'No, of course not,' said Colonel Julyan. 
'Now listen to me, Ben. You remember the lady  

2081
02:57:45,680 --> 02:57:50,400
with the boat. Were you on the beach when 
she took her boat out for the last time?'

2082
02:57:51,760 --> 02:57:55,200
'You were there, weren't you?' 
said Favell, standing over Ben.  

2083
02:57:56,080 --> 02:58:01,439
'You saw Mrs de Winter go into the cottage 
and Mr de Winter too. What happened then?'

2084
02:58:02,640 --> 02:58:04,880
Ben shook his head and 
moved back against the wall.  

2085
02:58:05,840 --> 02:58:09,920
'I didn't see anything,' he said. He began to cry.

2086
02:58:11,120 --> 02:58:15,920
'You damned little idiot,' Favell said slowly.

2087
02:58:17,520 --> 02:58:20,800
'I think Ben can go home now, 
don't you, Colonel Julyan?'  

2088
02:58:20,800 --> 02:58:25,279
Maxim said. Frank took Ben out of the 
room as the Colonel nodded his head.

2089
02:58:26,720 --> 02:58:29,120
'That poor fellow was terrified,' he said.  

2090
02:58:29,920 --> 02:58:33,600
'He's no use to you, Favell. I'm 
afraid you can't prove your story.'

2091
02:58:34,880 --> 02:58:38,240
Favell did not answer. Instead, he rang the bell  

2092
02:58:38,240 --> 02:58:42,399
and when Frith came in, he said, 'Ask 
Mrs Danvers to come here, Frith.'

2093
02:58:43,920 --> 02:58:48,560
'Isn't Mrs Danvers the housekeeper?' asked 
Colonel Julyan as Frith left the room.

2094
02:58:50,000 --> 02:58:56,560
'She was also Rebecca's friend. She knew her for 
years,' Favell said, with his unpleasant smile.

2095
02:58:57,680 --> 02:59:02,320
We all waited, watching the door. Then Mrs 
Danvers came in and shut the door behind her.

2096
02:59:03,600 --> 02:59:06,480
'Good evening, Mrs Danvers,' Colonel Julyan said.  

2097
02:59:07,279 --> 02:59:11,679
'I would like to ask you a question. 
You knew the late Mrs de Winter well.  

2098
02:59:12,880 --> 02:59:17,840
Mr Favell has told us that Mrs de Winter 
was in love with him. Is that true?'

2099
02:59:19,279 --> 02:59:22,240
'No, it is not,' Mrs Danvers answered.

2100
02:59:22,960 --> 02:59:27,840
'Now, listen, Danny,' Favell began to 
shout, but Mrs Danvers took no notice.

2101
02:59:29,279 --> 02:59:34,080
'She was not in love with you, Mr Jack. Or 
with Mr de Winter. She was not in love with  

2102
02:59:34,080 --> 02:59:39,279
anyone. She thought men were fools. She 
amused herself with you, that was all.'

2103
02:59:40,720 --> 02:59:45,840
Maxim went very white. Favell stared at Mrs 
Danvers as though he did not understand her.

2104
02:59:47,200 --> 02:59:49,920
'Mrs Danvers,' Colonel Julyan said quietly,  

2105
02:59:50,720 --> 02:59:54,160
'can you think of any reason why 
Mrs de Winter killed herself?'

2106
02:59:55,200 --> 03:00:00,240
Mrs Danvers shook her head. 
'No, certainly not,' she said.

2107
03:00:01,120 --> 03:00:04,640
'There you are! What did I 
tell you?' Favell shouted.

2108
03:00:05,279 --> 03:00:11,599
'Be quiet, will you. Let Mrs Danvers read the 
note. She may understand it,' Colonel Julyan said.  

2109
03:00:12,640 --> 03:00:15,920
Mrs Danvers took the note, read 
it and then shook her head again.

2110
03:00:17,439 --> 03:00:21,759
'I don't know what she meant. If it was 
something important, she would have told me.'

2111
03:00:23,120 --> 03:00:26,399
'Can you tell us how Mrs de Winter 
spent that last day in London?  

2112
03:00:27,279 --> 03:00:30,000
Did she keep a diary?' asked Colonel Julyan.

2113
03:00:31,279 --> 03:00:34,559
'I've got her diary in my 
room,' Mrs Danvers replied.  

2114
03:00:35,200 --> 03:00:37,840
'I kept all her things. I'll go and get it.'

2115
03:00:39,840 --> 03:00:44,480
'Well, de Winter,' said Colonel Julyan, 
'do you mind us seeing this diary?'

2116
03:00:45,680 --> 03:00:51,840
'Of course not,' said Maxim. Once again, I 
saw Colonel Julyan give Maxim a hard look.  

2117
03:00:52,399 --> 03:00:57,759
This time Frank saw it too. Somehow I felt 
sure that the truth was in that diary.

2118
03:00:59,200 --> 03:01:01,599
Mrs Danvers came back with 
a small book in her hand.

2119
03:01:03,200 --> 03:01:08,880
'Here is the page for the day Mrs de Winter died,' 
she said. Colonel Julyan looked at it carefully.

2120
03:01:10,080 --> 03:01:16,399
'Yes,' he said, 'here it is. Hairdressers 
at twelve o'clock. Then lunch. And  

2121
03:01:16,399 --> 03:01:24,399
then - Baker - two o'clock. Who was Baker?' 
He looked at Maxim. Maxim shook his head.

2122
03:01:25,520 --> 03:01:29,920
'Baker?' repeated Mrs Danvers. 
'She knew no one called Baker.'

2123
03:01:31,200 --> 03:01:34,399
'We must find out who this 
person was,' said Colonel Julyan.  

2124
03:01:35,359 --> 03:01:38,719
'If he wasn't a friend, perhaps 
it was someone she was afraid of.'

2125
03:01:40,160 --> 03:01:46,160
'Mrs de Winter afraid?' said Mrs Danvers. 
'She was afraid of nothing and no one.  

2126
03:01:46,960 --> 03:01:52,480
Only one thing worried her. That was the 
thought of illness, of dying slowly in her bed.'

2127
03:01:53,840 --> 03:01:59,360
'What does all this matter?' said Favell. 'If 
Baker was important Danny would know about him.'  

2128
03:02:00,319 --> 03:02:02,719
Mrs Danvers was turning the pages of the diary.

2129
03:02:03,520 --> 03:02:08,161
'There's a telephone number here at the 
back,' she said. 'And the name Baker again.'

2130
03:02:09,520 --> 03:02:14,400
'Well,' said Maxim, lighting a cigarette. 
'Perhaps someone should phone that number.  

2131
03:02:15,120 --> 03:02:16,160
Would you mind, Frank?'

2132
03:02:17,520 --> 03:02:22,960
Frank took the diary without a word and went 
into the next room. He shut the door behind him.  

2133
03:02:23,760 --> 03:02:27,680
When he came back, he said, 
'That was a doctor's number.  

2134
03:02:27,680 --> 03:02:30,640
Dr Baker used to live there, 
but he left six months ago.  

2135
03:02:31,840 --> 03:02:37,279
They gave me his new address. I have written 
it here.' And Frank held out a piece of paper.

2136
03:02:38,479 --> 03:02:43,839
It was then that Maxim looked at me. He looked at 
me like a man saying goodbye for the last time.  

2137
03:02:45,040 --> 03:02:47,519
That piece of paper was enough to hang Maxim.

2138
03:02:49,359 --> 03:02:53,759
I knew why Rebecca had gone to a doctor. 
I knew what she had wanted to tell Favell.  

2139
03:02:54,560 --> 03:02:58,000
Rebecca had been pregnant when 
she died. She had been going  

2140
03:02:58,000 --> 03:03:02,880
to have a child. It was the one clear 
proof that Rebecca had not killed herself.

2141
03:03:04,080 --> 03:03:08,000
I was sure that this was the 
truth. I knew Maxim thought so too.

2142
03:03:09,279 --> 03:03:14,000
'Well done, Frank,' said Maxim calmly. 
'Where does the doctor live now?'

2143
03:03:15,359 --> 03:03:22,799
'In north London,' Frank replied. 'But he's not on 
the phone. He's a very well-known women's doctor.'

2144
03:03:23,760 --> 03:03:27,920
'Well,' said Colonel Julyan. 'There must have 
been something wrong with her after all.'

2145
03:03:29,279 --> 03:03:31,439
'I'll write him a letter,' Frank said.

2146
03:03:32,160 --> 03:03:35,200
'I don't think he would tell 
you anything,' Colonel Julyan  

2147
03:03:35,200 --> 03:03:38,399
answered. 'I think de Winter 
should see him and explain.'

2148
03:03:39,600 --> 03:03:44,241
'I'm ready to go,' said Maxim quietly. 
'Shall I go up in the morning?'

2149
03:03:45,680 --> 03:03:49,680
'He's not going alone,' Favell said 
with a laugh. 'You go with him,  

2150
03:03:49,680 --> 03:03:54,080
Julyan. And I think I'd better 
go too. What time do we start?'

2151
03:03:54,080 --> 03:03:55,680
Colonel Julyan looked at Maxim.

2152
03:03:56,800 --> 03:04:00,400
'Nine o'clock?' he said. 'Perhaps 
you will take me in your car.'

2153
03:04:01,520 --> 03:04:06,081
'We'll meet at the crossroads just after 
nine,' Favell said. He walked to the door.

2154
03:04:07,120 --> 03:04:10,160
'I suppose you're not going to ask 
me to dinner, so I'll say goodbye.  

2155
03:04:11,040 --> 03:04:13,920
Come on, Danny. I'll see you in the morning, Max.'

2156
03:04:15,200 --> 03:04:17,200
Colonel Julyan came up to me and took my hand.

2157
03:04:18,240 --> 03:04:22,160
'Good night,' he said. 'Get 
your husband to bed early.  

2158
03:04:22,160 --> 03:04:26,479
Tomorrow will be a long day.' 
He held my hand for a moment,  

2159
03:04:26,479 --> 03:04:32,719
but he did not look into my eyes. He and Frank 
went out together. Maxim and I were alone at last.

2160
03:04:34,640 --> 03:04:36,720
'I'm coming with you tomorrow,' I said.

2161
03:04:37,680 --> 03:04:41,760
'Yes,' Maxim answered. 'We must 
be together as long as we can.'

2162
03:04:43,279 --> 03:04:49,200
I put my arms around him and held him. We 
did not say anything. Then Maxim held me  

2163
03:04:49,200 --> 03:05:03,840
tightly. We began to kiss each other, like 
guilty lovers who had never kissed before.
 
 

2164
03:05:11,120 --> 03:05:12,720
CHAPTER TWENTY THREE

2165
03:05:12,720 --> 03:05:13,440
Dr Baker

2166
03:05:14,960 --> 03:05:18,240
I woke up early the following 
morning at about six o'clock.  

2167
03:05:18,240 --> 03:05:22,479
I got up and went to the window. 
The trees were covered in mist.

2168
03:05:22,479 --> 03:05:26,080
There was a sharp coolness in 
the air. Autumn had arrived.

2169
03:05:27,359 --> 03:05:32,319
This was the start of a new day at Manderley. 
Soon the servants would be starting work.  

2170
03:05:33,520 --> 03:05:39,680
Whatever happened to us, life at Manderley would 
go on. The peace of Manderley could not be broken.  

2171
03:05:40,319 --> 03:05:44,719
Its beauty could not be destroyed. 
The flowers would come every year,  

2172
03:05:44,720 --> 03:05:50,320
the birds would sing. Manderley would always be 
here, safe and secure, within sound of the sea.

2173
03:05:52,000 --> 03:05:57,200
Maxim slept on and I did not wake him. 
The day ahead would be long and tiring.  

2174
03:05:57,200 --> 03:06:02,000
London was many miles away. We did not know 
what we should find at the end of the journey.

2175
03:06:04,080 --> 03:06:08,399
Somewhere in London lived a man called 
Baker. He had never heard of us.  

2176
03:06:08,399 --> 03:06:10,000
But our future was in his hands.

2177
03:06:11,439 --> 03:06:17,599
I had a bath, dressed and then woke Maxim. He 
got up and went into the bathroom. I began to  

2178
03:06:17,600 --> 03:06:23,279
pack a few things. We might have to stay 
overnight in London. I looked at my small  

2179
03:06:23,279 --> 03:06:29,840
case. It seemed so long since I had used it. But 
it was only four months. I could not believe it.

2180
03:06:31,600 --> 03:06:34,161
We had breakfast together and 
I went out on to the terrace.  

2181
03:06:34,800 --> 03:06:38,480
The air was fresh and clear now. 
It was going to be a perfect day.  

2182
03:06:39,760 --> 03:06:43,280
At nine o'clock exactly, Frank 
brought up Colonel Julyan in his car.

2183
03:06:44,319 --> 03:06:49,040
We were going in Maxim's car. I sat beside 
Maxim and Colonel Julyan got into the back.

2184
03:06:50,319 --> 03:06:53,759
'You will telephone, won't you?' 
Frank said as he stood on the steps.

2185
03:06:54,640 --> 03:06:59,520
'Yes, of course,' Maxim said. As we 
drove away, I looked back at the house.  

2186
03:07:00,319 --> 03:07:05,120
It had never looked more beautiful. For 
some reason, my eyes filled with tears.  

2187
03:07:06,000 --> 03:07:09,840
Then we were round the bend of the drive 
and I could see the house no longer.

2188
03:07:10,560 --> 03:07:13,440
When we came to the crossroads, 
Favell was already waiting.  

2189
03:07:14,160 --> 03:07:19,279
He waved when he saw us and started up his car. 
I settled down for the long journey to London.  

2190
03:07:20,240 --> 03:07:24,960
The hours passed and the miles went 
by, Favell's car always behind us.

2191
03:07:26,240 --> 03:07:31,200
We had lunch somewhere and reached London at 
about three o'clock. It was then that I began to  

2192
03:07:31,200 --> 03:07:37,519
feel tired. It was warm and the streets were busy. 
The drive through the centre of London seemed very  

2193
03:07:37,520 --> 03:07:44,880
long. Maxim looked pale and tired, but he did not 
say anything. Favell's car was always behind us.

2194
03:07:45,920 --> 03:07:52,080
We reached Baker's house at about five o'clock. 
Maxim stopped the car and we got out. Favell came  

2195
03:07:52,080 --> 03:07:58,080
up to meet us. We all walked slowly up the path 
to the front door. Colonel Julyan rang the bell.

2196
03:07:59,279 --> 03:08:00,399
A woman opened the door.

2197
03:08:01,359 --> 03:08:07,040
'Is Dr Baker at home?' said Colonel Julyan. 
'He is expecting us. I sent a telegram.'

2198
03:08:08,160 --> 03:08:14,000
'Yes, of course,' said the woman. 'My husband 
is in the garden. I'll tell him you are here.'

2199
03:08:15,359 --> 03:08:17,679
She took us into a cool room 
at the back of the house.  

2200
03:08:18,479 --> 03:08:21,679
She went out and in a few minutes 
a tall man came into the room.

2201
03:08:22,880 --> 03:08:28,000
'I'm Dr Baker. I'm sorry to keep you 
waiting. Please sit down,' he said.

2202
03:08:29,200 --> 03:08:35,720
'We are sorry to trouble you, Dr Baker,' Colonel 
Julyan said. 'My name is Julyan. This is Mr de  

2203
03:08:35,720 --> 03:08:41,840
Winter, Mrs de Winter and Mr Favell. We have 
come about the death of the late Mrs de Winter.  

2204
03:08:42,560 --> 03:08:44,640
You may have read the report in the papers.'

2205
03:08:45,600 --> 03:08:51,040
'The verdict was suicide,' Favell said. 'I 
knew Mrs de Winter very well. She did not kill  

2206
03:08:51,040 --> 03:08:56,560
herself. She had no reason to. We want to know 
why she came to see you on the day she died.'

2207
03:08:57,680 --> 03:09:02,000
Dr Baker looked surprised. 'I 
think you've made a mistake,'  

2208
03:09:02,000 --> 03:09:05,279
he said. 'No one called de 
Winter has ever come to me.'

2209
03:09:06,720 --> 03:09:10,400
'But we found your old telephone 
number in Mrs de Winter's diary.'  

2210
03:09:11,359 --> 03:09:16,240
Dr Baker looked at the page from the diary 
that Colonel Julyan was holding out to him.

2211
03:09:16,240 --> 03:09:18,800
'That certainly was my number,' he said.

2212
03:09:19,840 --> 03:09:24,000
'Perhaps Mrs de Winter gave you a 
different name,' Colonel Julyan suggested.

2213
03:09:25,040 --> 03:09:28,160
'It's possible,' said Dr Baker slowly.

2214
03:09:29,439 --> 03:09:32,479
'If you have any record of a visit 
on that day, could we see it?'  

2215
03:09:33,040 --> 03:09:36,000
Colonel Julyan asked. 'This 
is an important matter.'

2216
03:09:37,120 --> 03:09:38,720
'Murder,' Favell said.

2217
03:09:39,520 --> 03:09:43,840
'Of course,' said the doctor. 'I had 
no idea there was any question of that.  

2218
03:09:44,720 --> 03:09:45,760
I'll go and get my book.'

2219
03:09:47,279 --> 03:09:49,679
While Dr Baker was out of 
the room, we said nothing.  

2220
03:09:50,560 --> 03:09:54,960
No one looked at anyone else. Favell 
whistled quietly under his breath.

2221
03:09:56,239 --> 03:09:58,559
Dr Baker came back into 
the room with a large book.  

2222
03:09:59,279 --> 03:10:03,120
He opened the book and turned the 
pages. We all stood watching his face.

2223
03:10:04,479 --> 03:10:09,519
'I saw a Mrs Danvers on the 12th at 
two o'clock,' Dr Baker said at last.

2224
03:10:10,720 --> 03:10:15,200
'Danny? Why did...?' Favell began. Maxim broke in.

2225
03:10:16,000 --> 03:10:20,880
'Rebecca gave the wrong name, of course,' 
he said. 'Do you remember the visit now,  

2226
03:10:20,880 --> 03:10:26,560
Doctor?' But Dr Baker was already searching 
his files. He picked out a card and read it.

2227
03:10:27,600 --> 03:10:31,360
'Yes,' he said slowly, 'I remember now.'

2228
03:10:32,640 --> 03:10:36,960
'Was she tall and dark, a beautiful 
woman?' Colonel Julyan asked.

2229
03:10:37,920 --> 03:10:44,720
'Yes,' said Dr Baker. He put back the card 
and looked at Maxim. The doctor spoke slowly.

2230
03:10:46,080 --> 03:10:52,319
'The woman who called herself Mrs Danvers was 
very ill indeed. She had come to me the week  

2231
03:10:52,319 --> 03:10:59,519
before. I took some X-rays. She had come back to 
hear the result. I remember her words exactly.  

2232
03:11:00,399 --> 03:11:07,839
"I want to know the truth," she said. "If I'm 
really ill, I want to know." So I told her.'

2233
03:11:08,640 --> 03:11:10,800
Dr Baker stopped and looked down at the files.

2234
03:11:11,920 --> 03:11:16,080
'There was nothing to be done,' he went 
on. 'An operation would have been useless.  

2235
03:11:16,800 --> 03:11:21,840
I told her that. In six months, 
she would have been dead.'

2236
03:11:22,720 --> 03:11:27,840
No one said a word and the doctor went 
on, 'Mrs de Winter looked a healthy woman.  

2237
03:11:28,399 --> 03:11:34,239
She had very little pain at that time. But 
the pain would have come. The X-rays showed  

2238
03:11:34,239 --> 03:11:38,479
that she could never have had a child. But 
that was nothing to do with her illness.'

2239
03:11:39,840 --> 03:11:45,120
Everyone was standing up. We shook hands with Dr 
Baker and he walked with us to the front door.

2240
03:11:46,080 --> 03:11:48,960
'Shall I send you my report?' Dr Baker asked.

2241
03:11:49,600 --> 03:11:55,280
'We may not need it,' said Colonel Julyan. 'We'll 
write to you if we do. Thank you very much.'

2242
03:11:56,399 --> 03:12:03,839
'I am glad to have been of some use,' said 
Dr Baker. 'Goodbye.' And he shut the door.
 
 

2243
03:12:11,520 --> 03:12:13,279
CHAPTER TWENTY FOUR

2244
03:12:13,279 --> 03:12:14,719
The Return to Manderley

2245
03:12:17,200 --> 03:12:21,120
We went and stood by the car. No 
one said anything for a few minutes.  

2246
03:12:21,760 --> 03:12:25,680
Favell's face was grey. His hand 
shook as he lit a cigarette.

2247
03:12:26,880 --> 03:12:32,720
'She kept it a secret from everyone, even Danny. 
It's been a dreadful shock to me,' Favell said.  

2248
03:12:33,600 --> 03:12:36,640
'You're all right, of course, Max. 
You've been lucky, haven't you?  

2249
03:12:37,200 --> 03:12:39,840
You and your young wife can 
go back to Manderley now.  

2250
03:12:40,640 --> 03:12:46,000
You think you've won, but don't be too 
sure, I haven't finished with you yet.'

2251
03:12:46,000 --> 03:12:49,920
'Shall we get into the car and 
go?' Colonel Julyan asked Maxim.  

2252
03:12:50,880 --> 03:12:56,400
Favell smiled unpleasantly. As we drove away, 
he was still standing there, watching us.

2253
03:12:58,080 --> 03:13:00,880
'Favell can't do anything,' 
Colonel Julyan told us.  

2254
03:13:01,520 --> 03:13:06,000
'I'll soon deal with him if he comes near 
Manderley again. I don't think the papers will  

2255
03:13:06,000 --> 03:13:10,880
bother you any more. There may be some talk, but 
I'll make sure that people hear about Dr Baker.'

2256
03:13:12,160 --> 03:13:14,160
'Thank you very much,' Maxim said.

2257
03:13:15,200 --> 03:13:20,319
'What a dreadful thing illness is,' Colonel 
Julyan went on. 'I suppose she could not  

2258
03:13:20,319 --> 03:13:26,319
face the pain. She was such a lovely young 
woman, too.' Neither of us answered him.

2259
03:13:27,439 --> 03:13:31,599
Colonel Julyan's sister lived in London and 
he asked Maxim to take him to her house.

2260
03:13:32,960 --> 03:13:37,200
'We must thank you for all your help,' Maxim 
said as the magistrate got out of the car.

2261
03:13:38,080 --> 03:13:40,960
'I've been glad to help. 
You must forget it all now.  

2262
03:13:41,600 --> 03:13:46,960
Why don't you have a holiday, go abroad perhaps. 
Goodbye, both of you. It's been a long day.'

2263
03:13:48,720 --> 03:13:53,120
As Maxim started up the car, I leant 
back in my seat and closed my eyes.  

2264
03:13:54,000 --> 03:13:59,120
We drove on through the traffic and I felt 
full of peace. Nothing could hurt us any more.

2265
03:14:00,399 --> 03:14:03,439
We had dinner in a restaurant 
and Maxim phoned Frank.

2266
03:14:05,040 --> 03:14:08,239
'Do you think Colonel Julyan knows 
the truth about Rebecca's death?'  

2267
03:14:08,239 --> 03:14:10,319
I asked Maxim as we were drinking our coffee.

2268
03:14:11,359 --> 03:14:17,759
'Of course he knows,' Maxim said. 'But he will 
never say anything. I believe that Rebecca lied to  

2269
03:14:17,760 --> 03:14:24,640
me on purpose. She wanted me to kill her. That's 
why she laughed. She was laughing when she died.'

2270
03:14:26,160 --> 03:14:32,559
I did not say anything. It was all over. There was 
no need for Maxim to look so white and troubled.

2271
03:14:33,840 --> 03:14:37,840
'I'm not sure that Rebecca hasn't 
won, even now,' Maxim went on.  

2272
03:14:38,560 --> 03:14:43,680
'Frank told me something rather strange on 
the phone. Mrs Danvers has left Manderley.  

2273
03:14:44,399 --> 03:14:49,359
There was a long-distance call for her at 
six. By a quarter to seven, she had gone.'

2274
03:14:50,800 --> 03:14:56,960
'Isn't that a good thing?' I said. 'Favell phoned 
her, of course. But they can't do anything to us.'

2275
03:14:58,640 --> 03:15:02,560
I was glad that Mrs Danvers had 
gone. Manderley could be ours.  

2276
03:15:03,600 --> 03:15:08,240
We would have people to stay. And soon, 
very soon Maxim and I would have children.

2277
03:15:09,600 --> 03:15:12,480
'Have you finished your coffee?' 
Maxim said to me suddenly.  

2278
03:15:13,359 --> 03:15:18,399
'I feel that we must get back to Manderley as soon 
as possible. Something's wrong, I know it is.'

2279
03:15:19,600 --> 03:15:21,520
'But you'll be so tired,' I said.

2280
03:15:22,239 --> 03:15:25,359
'No, I shall be all right. We can 
be at Manderley by two o'clock.'

2281
03:15:27,120 --> 03:15:32,800
We went out to the car and Maxim covered me with 
a rug. It was dark now and I fell asleep almost  

2282
03:15:32,800 --> 03:15:40,239
at once. I started to dream. I saw the staircase 
at Manderley and Mrs Danvers standing there in  

2283
03:15:40,239 --> 03:15:46,399
her long, black dress. Then, in my dream, 
I was alone in the woods near Manderley.  

2284
03:15:47,439 --> 03:15:50,319
I wanted to get to the Happy 
Valley, but I could not find it.  

2285
03:15:51,120 --> 03:15:56,479
The dark trees were all round me. Then I 
was standing on the terrace. Moonlight shone  

2286
03:15:56,479 --> 03:16:01,839
on the windows. The gardens had gone and the 
dark woods came up to the walls of the house.

2287
03:16:03,040 --> 03:16:04,160
I woke up suddenly.

2288
03:16:05,600 --> 03:16:11,280
'You've slept for two hours,' Maxim told me. 'It's 
quarter past two. We shall be home by three.'

2289
03:16:13,359 --> 03:16:17,679
The early morning was very cold. The sky 
was dark now and there were no stars.

2290
03:16:19,120 --> 03:16:21,599
'What time did you say it was?' I said suddenly.

2291
03:16:22,479 --> 03:16:24,959
'It's twenty past two,' Maxim replied.

2292
03:16:25,920 --> 03:16:31,600
'That's strange,' I said. 'The dawn seems to 
be coming up over there, behind those hills.  

2293
03:16:32,399 --> 03:16:34,479
But it can't be, it's too early.'

2294
03:16:35,520 --> 03:16:39,201
'It's the wrong direction, too,' 
Maxim said 'you're looking west.'

2295
03:16:40,720 --> 03:16:44,160
I went on watching the sky. 
It was still getting lighter.  

2296
03:16:45,040 --> 03:16:51,359
A blood-red light was spreading across the 
sky. Maxim began to drive faster, much faster.

2297
03:16:52,479 --> 03:16:55,519
'That's not the dawn,' he 
said, 'that's Manderley.'

2298
03:16:57,439 --> 03:17:03,679
We reached the top of the hill. The road to 
Manderley lay before us. There was no moon  

2299
03:17:03,680 --> 03:17:09,201
and the sky above our heads was black. But the 
sky in front of us was full of dreadful light.  

2300
03:17:10,239 --> 03:17:16,559
And the light was red, red like blood. 
The wind blew towards us from the sea.  

2301
03:17:17,840 --> 03:17:25,840
The wind smelt of smoke and it was grey with 
ashes. They were the ashes of Manderley.
 
 
 
 
 
 

2302
03:17:41,000 --> 03:17:42,000
-  

2303
03:17:42,000 --> 03:17:42,500
THE END -

